<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7609</anchor> <rss>jms-00CD.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CD</addr>  <route>jms-00CD.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" addr="joyal-moerdijk-1995" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> that is a fixed point, i.e. the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. We may define the <em>induced <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra</em> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> to have the same carrier object as <tex>X</tex> and with the algebra map <tex>{ T X } \xrightarrow {{ \alpha _{ \bar { X } } }}{ X }</tex> defined as follows:

  
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/de2a8c68e6f961d45acdef0194c58333.svg"/></center>
  </p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7610</anchor> <rss>jms-00CF.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CF</addr>  <route>jms-00CF.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced monad algebra on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We must show that our <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">construction</link> in fact gives rise to a monad algebra.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7611</anchor> <rss>jms-00CE.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CE</addr>  <route>jms-00CE.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Unitality of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">unital</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 

  <p>We are trying to check that the following morphism is an identity:</p>
  
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/2a359c9040a55f2ef4f614d97cbf7314.svg"/></center>
  
 


  <ol><li>We unfold the definition of the algebra map <tex>\alpha _{ \bar { X } }</tex>.
      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/0f87c35b39a00d8f85fac9c9d009616f.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the unit law for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/c2c5003ba3cca14ae6a4d87de68ead02.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Finally, we use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> is inverse to <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/3938e2c26a9da32e674402dd41484644.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7612</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>We are trying to check that the following identity holds:</p>

  
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/1f1193a3eab173c1a6ba3385d30010ea.svg"/></center>
  
 


  <ol><li>
      We will start on the right-hand side. We first unfold the definition of the algebra map.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/8b1fad34eae4715b0df99cba362094b4.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> inverts <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/9502b0606db0133dc439ec822ac5db1d.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the associativity of the monad <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.
      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/3b4c0f7ae50ffa5b83242c06e08a5b2e.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Folding the definition of the algebra map, we have the desired cell.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/b6f160505cc15ff67459b461d8abf0e4.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7613</anchor> <rss>jms-00CH.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00CH</addr>  <route>jms-00CH.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> is a monad algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is in fact a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  Because it is <link href="jms-00CE.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CE" title="Unitality of the induced monad algebra">unital</link> and <link href="jms-00CG.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CG" title="Associativity of the induced monad algebra">associative</link>.
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7614</anchor> <rss>jms-00CK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CK</addr>  <route>jms-00CK.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" addr="joyal-moerdijk-1995" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \mathopen {} \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra equipped with an endomap <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ x }}{ X } \in \mathcal {C}</tex>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>x \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CQ" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> along <tex>x</tex>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>Suppose that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> is a homomorphism; we must check that the same map tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>.</p>

  <ol><li>
      First, we unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/bc269cb2ec0b1d077366e80a44b818e8.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Next, we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/afd46c27ca53f440080d78aee24ba545.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We unfold the restricted algebra map.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/e198e860c983e3e629de635ffcd4b0e4.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Then we use the associativity law for the algebra <tex>X</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/23a621442644a6cbec62549d761a3500.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> again.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/6756b4da5a94eef73873cb1e82e4b9df.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We recall that <tex>\pi _{ I }</tex> and <tex>\alpha _{ I }</tex> are inverse.
      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/a4ddb2c7d2a706f3b88c896f34bd146c.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7615</anchor> <rss>jms-00C5.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C5</addr>  <route>jms-00C5.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv   { \mathopen {} \left ( T, \eta , \mu \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>. An <em>algebra</em> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C6" title="Algebra for an endofunctor"><tex>T</tex>-algebra</link> <tex>X</tex> satisfying the following unit and associativity laws:</p>
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/ec6a76ddc3435d02090d7de7c24b35de.svg"/></center>
  
 

 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/0bd66da8e0c8dcb5cb15460a8ef974d8.svg"/></center>
  
 
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7616</anchor> <rss>jms-00C8.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00C8</addr>  <route>jms-00C8.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Weak algebra for a monad</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We shall refer to an <link href="jms-00C6.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C6" title="Algebra for an endofunctor">algebra</link> for the underlying endofunctor of a monad as a <em>weak algebra</em>, following <link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" addr="joyal-moerdijk-1995" title="Algebraic set theory">Joyal and Moerdijk</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7617</anchor> <rss>jms-00D9.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00D9</addr>  <route>jms-00D9.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>5</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>From <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CA" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra</link> homomorphisms to <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" addr="joyal-moerdijk-1995" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \mathopen {} \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C9" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link>. Then a <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CA" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex> also tracks a weak algebra homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot  X }</tex>,  where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CN" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>s \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CC" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>We work backwards.</p>

  <ol><li>
      First, we unfold the algebra structure of the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CC" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/4ee7eb58f0e5a95bad335dd39bc1076d.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We then use the <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CA" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> property of <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/fbf0fd45682f8b0d19870cbf674376c0.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Next we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism</link> property of <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/7aafc8995d6c3d4bb7b9e70188a2aeb3.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/5c41ffc567bce43e2c4f02ad058e9522.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We unfold the successor map on the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CN" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/411d5e4f4a8e601294dd86c4cc8ac6d2.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We contract the composition of the initial (weak) algebra map with its inverse.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/3c664e20119c1f06bb19c4aa73b2023c.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Finally, we use the unit law of the monad <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/f7ea0d87c91375db68dc3b992938e5a1.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7618</anchor> <rss>jms-00D8.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>jms-00D8</addr>  <route>jms-00D8.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>5</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>From initial <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">weak algebras</link> to initial <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C9" title="Successor algebra">successor algebras</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" addr="joyal-moerdijk-1995" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>I</tex> be the initial weak algebra for a monad <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CN" title="The induced successor algebra on a fixed point">induced successor algebra</link> <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <em>initial</em> <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C9" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>Let <tex>X</tex> be a successor algebra; <link href="jms-00CR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CR" title="Lifting homomorphisms to the induced successor algebra">we have shown</link> that weak algebra homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ \iota }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> from <tex>I</tex> to the <link href="jms-00CC.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CC" title="The successor restriction of a successor algebra">successor restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> also tracks a successor algebra homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ \iota }}{ X }</tex>. To see that this homomorphism is <em>unique</em>, fix any <link href="jms-00CA.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CA" title="Homomorphism of successor algebras">successor algebra homomorphism</link> <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>; we <link href="jms-00D9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00D9" title="From successor algebra homomorphisms to weak algebra homomorphisms">have also shown</link> that such a homomorphism also tracks a (<link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link>) homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ s \cdot X }</tex>. But <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ \iota }}{ s \cdot X }</tex> is the such weak algebra homomorphism, so we have <tex>\iota  = j</tex>.</p>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7619</anchor> <rss>jms-00CN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Construction</taxon> <addr>jms-00CN</addr>  <route>jms-00CN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C9" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T} \equiv { \mathopen {} \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>. The <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced by</link> <tex>X</tex> can be equipped with the structure of a <link href="jms-00C9.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C9" title="Successor algebra">successor algebra</link> by defining <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ s _{ \bar { X } } }}{ X }</tex> to be the following map:</p>
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/9a89b76b4a13a2dbaebe3bc60586d0b1.svg"/></center>
  
 
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7620</anchor> <rss>jms-00CK.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CK</addr>  <route>jms-00CK.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>31</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Lifting <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">homomorphisms</link> to the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> <meta name="source"><link href="joyal-moerdijk-1995.xml" type="local" addr="joyal-moerdijk-1995" title="Algebraic set theory">[joyal-moerdijk-1995]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}   \equiv { \mathopen {} \left ( T , \eta , \mu \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex> and let <tex>I</tex> be an invertible <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad"><em>weak</em> algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>; let <tex>X</tex> be an arbitrary <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>-algebra equipped with an endomap <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ x }}{ X } \in \mathcal {C}</tex>. Then a homomorphism <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> also tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>, where <tex>\bar { I }</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> of <tex>I</tex> and <tex>x \cdot X</tex> is the <link href="jms-00CQ.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CQ" title="Restricting endofunctor algebras along endomorphisms">restriction</link> of <tex>X</tex> along <tex>x</tex>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>Suppose that <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> is a homomorphism; we must check that the same map tracks a homomorphism <tex>{ \bar { I } } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ X }</tex>.</p>

  <ol><li>
      First, we unfold the definition of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/bc269cb2ec0b1d077366e80a44b818e8.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Next, we use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/afd46c27ca53f440080d78aee24ba545.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We unfold the restricted algebra map.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/e198e860c983e3e629de635ffcd4b0e4.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Then we use the associativity law for the algebra <tex>X</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/23a621442644a6cbec62549d761a3500.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the <link href="jms-00C7.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C7" title="Homomorphism of algebras">algebra homomorphism law</link> for <tex>{ I } \xrightarrow {{ j }}{ x \cdot X }</tex> again.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/6756b4da5a94eef73873cb1e82e4b9df.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We recall that <tex>\pi _{ I }</tex> and <tex>\alpha _{ I }</tex> are inverse.
      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/a4ddb2c7d2a706f3b88c896f34bd146c.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7621</anchor> <rss>jms-00CH.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-00CH</addr>  <route>jms-00CH.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> is a monad algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is in fact a <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">monad algebra</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  Because it is <link href="jms-00CE.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CE" title="Unitality of the induced monad algebra">unital</link> and <link href="jms-00CG.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CG" title="Associativity of the induced monad algebra">associative</link>.
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7622</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 
  <p>We are trying to check that the following identity holds:</p>

  
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/1f1193a3eab173c1a6ba3385d30010ea.svg"/></center>
  
 


  <ol><li>
      We will start on the right-hand side. We first unfold the definition of the algebra map.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/8b1fad34eae4715b0df99cba362094b4.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> inverts <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/9502b0606db0133dc439ec822ac5db1d.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the associativity of the monad <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.
      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/3b4c0f7ae50ffa5b83242c06e08a5b2e.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Folding the definition of the algebra map, we have the desired cell.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/b6f160505cc15ff67459b461d8abf0e4.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7623</anchor> <rss>jms-00CF.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00CF</addr>  <route>jms-00CF.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The induced monad algebra on a fixed point</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We must show that our <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">construction</link> in fact gives rise to a monad algebra.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7624</anchor> <rss>jms-00CE.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CE</addr>  <route>jms-00CE.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Unitality of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">unital</link>.</p>
  
    <block open="open"><headline><strong>Proof</strong>.</headline> 

  <p>We are trying to check that the following morphism is an identity:</p>
  
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/2a359c9040a55f2ef4f614d97cbf7314.svg"/></center>
  
 


  <ol><li>We unfold the definition of the algebra map <tex>\alpha _{ \bar { X } }</tex>.
      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/0f87c35b39a00d8f85fac9c9d009616f.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      We use the unit law for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/c2c5003ba3cca14ae6a4d87de68ead02.svg"/></center>
  </li>

    <li>
      Finally, we use the fact that <tex>\pi _{ X }</tex> is inverse to <tex>\alpha _{ X }</tex>.

      
 
  
  
    <center><img src="resources/3938e2c26a9da32e674402dd41484644.svg"/></center>
  </li></ol>
</block>
  
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>7625</anchor> <rss>jms-00CG.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-00CG</addr>  <route>jms-00CG.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>30</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Associativity of the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> be a monad on a category <tex>\mathcal {C}</tex>, and let <tex>X</tex> be a <link href="jms-00C8.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C8" title="Weak algebra for a monad">weak algebra</link> for <tex>\mathbb {T}</tex> for which the algebra map is invertible by <tex>{ X } \xrightarrow {{ \pi _{ X } }}{ T X }</tex>. Then the <link href="jms-00CD.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00CD" title="The induced monad algebra">induced monad algebra</link> <tex>\bar { X }</tex> is <link href="jms-00C5.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00C5" title="Algebra for a monad">associative</link>.</p>
  
